WEBVTT

00:01.570 --> 00:05.456
Reading from verse Peter, it's near the end.

00:06.818 --> 00:20.779
Verse Peter chapter three, verses 13 to 18. Who is going to harm you if you are eager to do good?

00:22.121 --> 00:26.388
But even if you should suffer for what is right, you are blessed.

00:27.089 --> 00:28.571
Do not fear their threats.

00:29.132 --> 00:30.674
Do not be frightened.

00:31.426 --> 00:35.551
but in your hearts, reverb Christ as Lord.

00:35.571 --> 00:44.081
Always be prepared to give an answer to anyone who asks you to give the reason for the hope that you have.

00:45.263 --> 01:01.362
But do this with gentleness and respect, keeping a clear conscience so that those who speak maliciously against your good behavior in Christ may be ashamed of their slander

01:02.434 --> 01:13.069
For it is better if it is God's will to suffer for doing good rather than doing evil.

01:14.111 --> 01:22.563
For Christ also suffered once for sins, the righteous for the unrighteous to bring you to God.

01:23.784 --> 01:30.514
He was put to death in the body but made alive in the spirit.

01:31.298 --> 01:33.361
This is the word of the Lord.

01:37.468 --> 01:38.089
Please be seated.

01:44.580 --> 01:47.624
Quick poll, how many of you were born in Calgary?

01:50.970 --> 01:54.115
Okay, about 35% of you, we would like to shake your hand.

01:55.437 --> 01:58.482
On behalf of the rest of us who moved here, thank you.

01:59.970 --> 02:01.912
It is great to be in this city.

02:02.693 --> 02:06.577
I moved here a little over 22 years ago now, coming up on 23.

02:07.859 --> 02:09.641
And I came from Regina, Saskatchewan.

02:10.562 --> 02:11.983
And what I, yes.

02:14.746 --> 02:15.767
You can forgive me too.

02:16.928 --> 02:20.592
When we moved here, I discovered something interesting when we were looking at houses.

02:21.093 --> 02:21.874
Here's what I discovered.

02:21.894 --> 02:22.835
I never knew this before.

02:23.576 --> 02:29.362
That when you walked around the house, if you could see out of any window at any place to catch any glimpse

02:29.666 --> 02:33.652
of a certain aspect of reality, you would hit the jackpot.

02:34.553 --> 02:43.746
If you could see a sliver of the mountains out of the guest bedroom, the third guest bedroom, you had what was called a mountain view.

02:47.211 --> 02:52.599
And it was there that I discovered the value of beauty.

02:52.639 --> 02:53.620
We love beauty.

02:54.662 --> 02:55.984
We love beauty here in Calgary.

02:56.644 --> 02:57.746
We value it.

02:58.210 --> 03:00.653
Our houses are more expensive if you've got a great view.

03:01.113 --> 03:02.715
We love the Rocky Mountains.

03:03.256 --> 03:03.856
We love them.

03:04.517 --> 03:07.240
We even love the new library.

03:07.881 --> 03:09.923
We might complain about how expensive it was, but we love it.

03:10.944 --> 03:15.049
It's also why we hate the big blue ring on the way out to the airport.

03:15.990 --> 03:17.551
You look at the thing, it's not beautiful.

03:18.152 --> 03:18.853
It's a ring.

03:20.655 --> 03:21.536
We love beauty.

03:21.576 --> 03:23.077
We care about beauty.

03:23.538 --> 03:25.060
We love it in our dining.

03:25.700 --> 03:27.282
Fine dining is defined.

03:27.490 --> 03:31.376
Not just by flavor and not just by if it will make you full, it won't.

03:33.659 --> 03:36.203
But how many swirls can they put on the plate?

03:37.485 --> 03:38.347
We love beauty.

03:39.168 --> 03:40.109
We'll pay for it.

03:41.351 --> 03:46.118
And yet we also realize this, that we live in a time defined by ugly conflict.

03:47.621 --> 03:48.622
It's getting ugly out there.

03:49.684 --> 03:51.046
You can go on social media.

03:51.867 --> 03:54.311
Any platform of your choice, it's ugly.

03:54.371 --> 03:56.274
You can turn on the news, it's ugly.

03:56.930 --> 03:58.432
People are at each other's throats.

03:59.394 --> 04:00.916
Political discourse is strained.

04:00.996 --> 04:02.638
Workplace dynamics are strained.

04:02.698 --> 04:07.465
Even if you go to the mall, you can feel the tension in people.

04:08.667 --> 04:09.969
You can sense it when you're driving.

04:10.690 --> 04:13.534
You hop on Crow Child Trail and you're like, this could turn into a fight.

04:16.218 --> 04:19.283
And we're both in rav force.

04:19.303 --> 04:20.284
We're not fighting people.

04:22.447 --> 04:24.210
We live in a time defined by ugly conflict.

04:26.562 --> 04:32.270
And one of the things that Peter tells us is that Jesus offers a new way of being human.

04:33.572 --> 04:35.756
That we don't have to be marked by ugly conflict.

04:36.196 --> 04:39.060
We can be marked by a beautiful hope.

04:40.002 --> 04:46.251
Peter says that Jesus has this invitation to a whole new kingdom, a whole new set of rules and reality.

04:48.174 --> 04:51.879
And that if you follow Jesus, there will be peace in the midst of trial.

04:52.841 --> 04:54.203
And our lives are marked by trial.

04:54.864 --> 04:56.466
Some of it's self-inflicted sure.

04:56.546 --> 05:01.974
Some of it is other-inflicted, and some of it is just the difficulty of walking through day-to-day life.

05:03.616 --> 05:04.697
We experience it.

05:05.559 --> 05:14.151
And finally, Peter says this, in Jesus, you have hope for a home, life after life, what people often refer to as heaven.

05:14.571 --> 05:16.594
So today we're going to talk about the beauty of hope.

05:17.570 --> 05:28.705
It's also part of why we've been in this revisioning time as a church for about the past year and why we're stepping into it now is because we believe this, that a world that has ugly conflict needs a beautiful savior.

05:30.688 --> 05:31.929
That actually needs hope.

05:32.270 --> 05:36.235
That the average Calgarian is desperate for hope.

05:37.978 --> 05:47.090
And so that's why we're doing this series, why we've had focus groups in prayer and why we're talking and asking and calling us a church to change.

05:48.386 --> 05:52.912
because we can't live in autopilot and change a world that's getting uglier.

05:54.154 --> 05:55.936
So today we're gonna talk about the beauty of hope.

05:56.117 --> 05:57.158
So we're gonna have a number of prayers.

05:57.418 --> 05:59.441
Some of you, we're gonna invite you to pray.

05:59.501 --> 06:02.605
Prayer is this, it's speaking to God and listening for His voice.

06:03.427 --> 06:04.688
Some of you here, you're exploring.

06:05.650 --> 06:10.056
Some of you are here and you've just forgotten the great hope we have in Jesus.

06:10.756 --> 06:13.961
And so today is an amazing day to ask Him to restore that.

06:15.102 --> 06:17.746
And then some of us, we're walking in the hope of Christ

06:17.986 --> 06:24.835
Look at this beautiful hope, and yet it's not meant to be contained just for you, that if you're blessed, you're blessed to be a blessing.

06:25.677 --> 06:30.203
So we're gonna talk about how we're gonna pray about becoming that to the rest of our city and beyond.

06:30.884 --> 06:32.766
So that being said, I invite us to pray, let's pray together.

06:37.313 --> 06:42.840
Father, you sent your son Jesus into the world to bring good news and to bring hope.

06:43.942 --> 06:46.866
You didn't send your son into the world to condemn it, but to save it.

06:49.346 --> 06:57.578
So Jesus, there are people in this room and watching online who've never experienced your new life and the hope that it brings.

06:58.679 --> 07:01.804
Today, would you reveal it to them and give them the gift of faith?

07:03.446 --> 07:04.548
God, some of us are in the room.

07:04.588 --> 07:07.872
We've maybe been around church or been in church for a long time.

07:08.413 --> 07:10.476
And we had hope and yet it slipped away.

07:10.496 --> 07:11.197
It's grown dull.

07:12.439 --> 07:13.841
Maybe through pain or trial.

07:15.904 --> 07:17.426
Everything's kind of just gone great.

07:19.170 --> 07:23.478
Would you restore hope today in Jesus' name?

07:23.498 --> 07:27.266
And finally, some of us, Lord, are walking with lots of hope.

07:28.749 --> 07:30.993
Pray that we wouldn't just hold that in for ourselves.

07:31.013 --> 07:41.533
Would you teach us how to hold it out to others so they might experience your great love, your great forgiveness, your great strength, and your great beauty in Jesus' name?

07:41.553 --> 07:41.874
Amen.

07:42.626 --> 07:46.031
So if you've got a Bible, you can flip to first Peter chapter three, that's where we're gonna be.

07:46.131 --> 07:47.293
We've been in the book of first Peter.

07:47.894 --> 07:51.399
As we've been working through this vision series, we will be next week.

07:51.419 --> 07:56.947
As we talk about a beautiful hope, we have three major ideas about how to live a life of beautiful hope.

07:57.648 --> 08:00.952
The first is this, to live a life of beautiful goodness.

08:01.834 --> 08:02.515
Beautiful goodness.

08:03.476 --> 08:07.642
And then we'll explore the second idea, a kind of an oxymoron, beautiful suffering.

08:08.403 --> 08:10.546
What none of us wish for and all of us will get.

08:11.330 --> 08:14.113
and then we'll end off with this idea of a beautiful hope.

08:15.175 --> 08:17.898
So here's where we pick up as we talk about beautiful goodness.

08:18.338 --> 08:22.003
A little bit of background, Peter, he is now the lead leader in the church.

08:22.824 --> 08:25.907
He leads amongst a multitude of leaders, but he is the lead leader.

08:26.588 --> 08:32.796
And he writes this letter to a group of churches that are scattered around the province of what was called Asia Minor.

08:33.156 --> 08:34.898
What we now know is the country of Turkey.

08:35.618 --> 08:44.106
And so he's writing to people, and these are people who've experienced this hope of Jesus, and yet, they're beginning to feel some pushback from the culture.

08:45.348 --> 08:49.692
So in the history of the church, there are times where you would die for being a Christian.

08:50.313 --> 08:52.475
There are many places around the world where that's the case.

08:53.255 --> 08:55.197
And we should pray for those people, and we often do.

08:56.779 --> 09:03.986
At this time, however, that Peter's writing, you wouldn't get thrown to the lions, you'd just get laughed at if you were a Christian.

09:05.474 --> 09:08.178
it wouldn't mean death, it would mean dishonor.

09:09.561 --> 09:19.937
However, in an honor society culture, or honor shame society rather, if you were dishonorable, it had big ramifications for your economic life.

09:20.738 --> 09:28.671
So at this time, in this region of the world, if you wouldn't worship the empire by worshiping the emperor, here's what would happen.

09:29.472 --> 09:33.138
If you were a tradesperson, say you were a seamstress,

09:33.858 --> 09:38.302
or you were a craftsman or a bricklayer, you were a part of what was called a guild.

09:38.322 --> 09:41.005
And in order to work, you had to be a part of the guild.

09:41.746 --> 09:45.389
In some ways, it was kind of like a modern day union, except it was government instituted.

09:46.370 --> 09:50.054
If you would not worship the emperor, you could not be a part of a guild.

09:51.235 --> 09:51.935
Here's what that meant.

09:53.557 --> 09:56.540
If you were a Christian, you couldn't have a regular job.

09:57.821 --> 09:59.963
So you'd pick up the worst kind of jobs.

09:59.983 --> 10:03.026
That's the kind of difficulty these people were enduring.

10:03.906 --> 10:06.569
And so that's where Peter picks up and where we pick up our time.

10:07.650 --> 10:11.053
And Peter gives us, what do you do when you're feeling the social pressure?

10:11.934 --> 10:12.514
So here's the big deal.

10:12.534 --> 10:17.819
If you're here exploring faith, if you actually become a Christian and you follow Jesus, there will be pushback.

10:17.839 --> 10:20.822
We're experiencing it more and more in Canada than ever before.

10:21.663 --> 10:23.845
And Peter goes, here's how you live in light of it.

10:25.126 --> 10:26.868
So, he begins with this.

10:27.248 --> 10:33.234
Who is going to harm you if you are eager to do good?

10:34.754 --> 10:36.697
So here Peter's gonna get immensely practical.

10:37.198 --> 10:38.059
He's gonna say, you know what?

10:38.079 --> 10:45.810
You might face social difficulty back then, and especially now, if you go, I believe this whole book.

10:46.932 --> 10:52.740
See, if you wanna live a Christian life with integrity, you have to go, I believe the whole thing, not just the parts I like.

10:54.123 --> 10:55.084
Not just the parts I like.

10:55.104 --> 10:57.668
This is so essential to living a life of faith.

10:58.289 --> 10:59.110
Here's why.

10:59.150 --> 11:04.658
Many of us, we struggle with this idea

11:04.994 --> 11:09.680
that the past is broken, and the church in the past, it did horrible things, right?

11:09.700 --> 11:19.192
So you can wind back about 80 years ago, and you can look at much of the racism that took place on this continent where we degraded black people.

11:19.212 --> 11:20.734
And a lot of church people did that.

11:22.677 --> 11:23.998
And people go, how could they do that?

11:24.098 --> 11:25.120
Here's how they could do it.

11:25.801 --> 11:32.029
They ignored Genesis one, two, and three, where it said, God made all people in His image.

11:32.049 --> 11:33.170
They just ignored that part.

11:33.954 --> 11:38.118
So we look back now and go, oh, I can't believe they did that.

11:38.979 --> 11:41.802
We look back even further to slavery and you go, how could they do that?

11:42.563 --> 11:44.585
You go, they ignored Genesis one, two, and three.

11:44.625 --> 11:51.431
And yet, what can often happen is we can live in what C.S.

11:51.451 --> 11:55.335
Lewis, a great author, called chronological snobbery.

11:57.017 --> 11:59.960
And so we would go, we would never make the mistakes that the people before us did.

12:01.541 --> 12:02.162
But,

12:03.010 --> 12:11.098
If you read this book and believe it, there are parts of it that are hard to live or believe or accept in Canadian society in 2026.

12:11.238 --> 12:13.240
It'll just cost you.

12:14.721 --> 12:26.372
But here's what we do when we trust that God can actually guide us is that when people look back 100 years from now at us, they're going to look at something and go, I can't believe they did that.

12:27.133 --> 12:28.074
That was crazy.

12:28.114 --> 12:32.498
And so,

12:33.442 --> 12:34.664
Peter gives us advice.

12:35.225 --> 12:40.474
How do you read and trust the whole book and have people laugh at you and yet get through?

12:40.554 --> 12:42.578
He says this, be eager to do good.

12:44.942 --> 12:45.303
Okay?

12:46.725 --> 12:48.428
Be eager to do good.

12:51.353 --> 12:52.255
So let me just use an example.

12:52.615 --> 12:55.701
Some of you are students, you're like teenagers or almost teenagers.

12:56.362 --> 12:58.706
And here's the big idea, at school you're gonna feel pressure.

12:59.426 --> 13:04.432
You'll feel pressure not to live a life in alignment with Jesus and with Scripture.

13:05.413 --> 13:18.970
But what happens if you're the number one student, the best student you can be, or you're the absolute best friend, or you're the person that everyone can trust, or if you're on a sports team, you're a great athlete and a great teammate.

13:19.831 --> 13:21.112
Guess what happens?

13:21.132 --> 13:25.778
It becomes very hard for people to mock you and to ride you and treat you like dirt.

13:28.866 --> 13:40.759
Conversely, if you work at CNRL, and you live a life of public faith, you're not annoying, you just go to work and you show up and you show up early, not too early.

13:40.779 --> 13:47.206
Okay, Christians, we also got to resist the urge to be engulfed by workaholism.

13:47.987 --> 13:50.250
But you show up early, you do a great job.

13:50.890 --> 13:54.795
You don't complain, you don't gossip, you support your boss, you support those underneath you.

13:55.215 --> 13:57.778
And then you leave late, not too late.

14:00.866 --> 14:04.591
And yet at times, you're vocal about your Christian faith.

14:04.831 --> 14:05.291
Guess what?

14:05.492 --> 14:10.918
It's very hard to fire the all-star on the team just because they're a Christian.

14:10.938 --> 14:12.580
You can apply this to any area of your life.

14:13.041 --> 14:14.142
Here's what Peter says.

14:15.804 --> 14:27.519
If you are gonna live for Jesus in a world with pressure, you have to be eager or zealous for good works.

14:28.860 --> 14:30.162
A lot of translations actually,

14:30.498 --> 14:34.983
That who is going to harm you if you're eager, that word eager there can also be translated zealous.

14:36.024 --> 14:42.030
And in the original language, that word there for zealous, actually just says if you are a zealot for good works.

14:43.272 --> 14:45.214
Now some of you might be going, I don't know what that means.

14:46.335 --> 14:47.036
What does that mean?

14:47.296 --> 14:47.957
Great question.

14:49.519 --> 14:53.383
At this time in Israel, there was political movements.

14:54.064 --> 14:54.864
There were sort of four of them.

14:54.884 --> 15:00.050
There was the Pharisees who were like the religious conservatives who hated Jesus.

15:00.738 --> 15:04.523
Because Jesus showed up in a way they were not expecting.

15:04.543 --> 15:06.827
He didn't fit their box.

15:06.847 --> 15:10.311
The Sadducees were sort of the religious progressives of the day.

15:10.372 --> 15:12.174
Everyone was religious in Jewish culture, by the way.

15:13.656 --> 15:16.720
And they didn't like Jesus because he took the whole book seriously.

15:17.221 --> 15:22.088
They thought he was backwards and an embecile and a backwater hick.

15:22.108 --> 15:23.570
Then there was the Herodians.

15:24.738 --> 15:28.564
These are people who, Jewish people who said, we're just gonna do whatever the government says.

15:28.644 --> 15:31.308
We're just gonna partner up with them, buddy up with them and just get through.

15:31.348 --> 15:36.656
And then the last group, the zealots.

15:36.676 --> 15:39.139
The zealots were secretly scheming.

15:39.159 --> 15:40.481
They were the militia of the day.

15:41.182 --> 15:46.190
They're like, let's get our swords and let's overthrow Rome.

15:46.831 --> 15:52.218
Eventually they will try to overthrow Rome and it leads to Jerusalem being torn apart and the temple being torn down.

15:53.120 --> 15:54.642
These were serious people.

15:55.202 --> 15:56.443
They were revolutionaries.

15:58.666 --> 16:05.574
And what Peter is saying is this, if you're gonna follow Jesus, you have to become a revolutionary for goodness.

16:08.718 --> 16:09.298
What does that mean?

16:09.579 --> 16:22.674
It means this, that if you wanna follow Jesus, the way Jesus would have you follow him is that you and I, we must become people of great virtue, like remarkable virtue.

16:23.010 --> 16:28.298
In fact, what the world needs, what Calgary needs is this, people who will follow Jesus and look just like their neighbors.

16:29.359 --> 16:35.107
And it will be the best neighbors, the best employees, the best students, the best spouses, the best friends.

16:37.050 --> 16:37.851
Because we have a hope.

16:39.954 --> 16:45.202
We've got a great hope that God sees, he knows, he cares and forgives our shortcomings.

16:53.698 --> 16:54.579
There's an old quote.

16:59.507 --> 17:01.029
Actually, one other quick aside.

17:02.351 --> 17:15.632
So, some of what can happen is this, Peter's saying this, if you're gonna follow Jesus and you're gonna take heat, because we will get to it, that there's a but here coming, it should be because we're living really moral, upstanding lives.

17:16.934 --> 17:19.538
There's a letter to a guy named Diagnetus.

17:19.970 --> 17:22.232
It's found, we found this letter, it's crazy, it's old letter.

17:22.593 --> 17:24.574
Diagnitus, who the heck is Diagnitus?

17:24.795 --> 17:25.976
A guy with a hard name to say.

17:27.157 --> 17:32.042
But he was also the tutor and mentor of Marcus Aurelius, one of the great Roman leaders.

17:33.063 --> 17:39.049
And he was writing to Marcus, there was a letter written to him, giving a report for him to give to Marcus Aurelius about Christians.

17:39.889 --> 17:41.631
Because Christians conquered the Roman Empire.

17:42.852 --> 17:43.132
We did.

17:43.193 --> 17:48.818
Here's how, in this letter it says this, Christians,

17:49.602 --> 17:55.210
are indistinguishable from other people, whether by nationality, language, or customs.

17:55.591 --> 17:57.354
They don't inhabit separate cities of their own.

17:57.915 --> 17:59.397
They don't speak a strange language.

17:59.958 --> 18:01.820
They don't live some outlandish way of life.

18:02.481 --> 18:05.927
They live in the flesh, but they are not governed by the desires of the flesh.

18:06.808 --> 18:11.415
They pass their days on earth, but they are citizens of heaven.

18:12.637 --> 18:16.803
Obedient to the laws, yet they live on a level that transcends the law.

18:17.204 --> 18:18.866
Christians love all people.

18:19.458 --> 18:26.387
but all people persecute them, condemned because they are not understood, they are put to death, but raised to life again.

18:26.828 --> 18:28.751
They live in poverty, but they enrich many.

18:29.051 --> 18:32.496
They are totally destitute, but possess an abundance of everything.

18:33.217 --> 18:37.242
They suffer dishonor, but that is their glory.

18:39.125 --> 18:45.494
Friends, it's incredibly hard to punish people who are relentlessly adding value.

18:48.338 --> 18:48.658
So,

18:48.802 --> 18:54.848
If you're here and you're a Christian, beautiful goodness is a billboard for Christian faith.

18:56.129 --> 18:59.352
People don't need them yelling at them about how Jesus is so good.

18:59.613 --> 19:04.157
What they need to see is people who talk about how good Jesus is and then live it out in every area of life.

19:05.218 --> 19:06.579
That's great advertising.

19:07.881 --> 19:10.203
And also, it's great protection.

19:11.504 --> 19:14.327
But let's talk now about beautiful suffering.

19:15.548 --> 19:17.490
Verse 14.

19:18.562 --> 19:19.403
So who's gonna harm you?

19:20.364 --> 19:21.185
And then we hit the reel.

19:21.565 --> 19:27.492
But even if you should suffer for what is right, you are blessed.

19:29.594 --> 19:30.435
You are blessed.

19:30.455 --> 19:32.337
Here Peter picks up on the language of Jesus.

19:32.777 --> 19:40.185
Jesus actually said, if people laugh at you and mock you for serving the kingdom of God, you're blessed.

19:40.205 --> 19:41.006
That's what happens.

19:41.867 --> 19:46.792
That people who really live in line with God, people start to push back on them.

19:46.812 --> 19:48.274
They don't like them.

19:48.418 --> 19:49.800
Why on earth would that be the case?

19:50.881 --> 19:56.508
Like if you love God, why would anybody push back on you, not like you, hate you, despise you?

19:56.568 --> 19:58.151
Here's why.

19:59.492 --> 20:01.675
Light always reveals darkness.

20:03.377 --> 20:04.479
Light always reveals darkness.

20:04.939 --> 20:05.360
What do I mean?

20:06.321 --> 20:07.442
I'm gonna use a couple analogies.

20:09.485 --> 20:12.108
You ever been around somebody really outrageously fit?

20:14.632 --> 20:16.434
Just that kid has.

20:18.754 --> 20:22.458
And you just around them and you're like, I just feel so out of shape.

20:23.840 --> 20:24.981
You kind of feel the ugliness.

20:25.282 --> 20:27.985
Heaven forbid you go out for lunch with them and order first.

20:30.067 --> 20:32.029
You go out for lunch with somebody really fit.

20:32.049 --> 20:33.631
You order, you're like, I'll get a hamburger.

20:33.892 --> 20:34.953
No, a cheeseburger.

20:35.233 --> 20:37.175
No, a bacon cheeseburger.

20:39.959 --> 20:40.660
Do you want salad?

20:41.260 --> 20:42.782
No, I want french fries.

20:43.863 --> 20:46.226
With mayo dip, yeah, with mayo dip.

20:47.010 --> 20:49.013
And then they ordered their like, I'll get a boiled chicken.

20:53.680 --> 20:54.822
With kale, exactly.

20:55.463 --> 20:56.624
And you know how you feel.

20:56.644 --> 20:56.705
No.

21:01.892 --> 21:02.834
We've also had it though.

21:02.874 --> 21:03.555
We've also had it.

21:04.496 --> 21:09.544
Where you go to a job and there's somebody who's just outshining you, or maybe you're a student, they're just outshining you.

21:09.844 --> 21:10.686
They're showing up early.

21:10.866 --> 21:11.627
They're working better.

21:11.867 --> 21:13.810
They're nice to the boss in your heart.

21:13.870 --> 21:14.752
You know, you've done it.

21:14.812 --> 21:15.192
I've done it.

21:15.212 --> 21:16.274
You're like, suck up.

21:21.122 --> 21:26.547
You can now align yourself with the highest moral good in the world and live it.

21:28.269 --> 21:29.370
It will create conflict.

21:30.992 --> 21:31.272
It will.

21:35.596 --> 21:40.982
When it creates conflict and you hear threats and it's hard, what do you do?

21:42.904 --> 21:46.487
Verse 15, in your hearts, revere Christ as Lord.

21:48.529 --> 21:49.330
This idea of

21:49.506 --> 21:51.528
Jesus being Lord is really important.

21:51.568 --> 21:52.229
Here's what it means.

21:52.850 --> 21:56.514
If someone was Lord in the ancient world, what that meant is they got to tell you what to do.

21:57.014 --> 21:57.435
And you did it.

21:58.095 --> 22:03.982
And you didn't complain, you didn't argue, and you didn't get a vote.

22:04.002 --> 22:04.662
They were in charge.

22:06.885 --> 22:07.826
So here's what happens.

22:09.648 --> 22:16.355
If you follow Jesus and you're living a virtuous life and there's pushback, there is now a battle for who gets to be in charge.

22:18.137 --> 22:19.058
Who gets to be in charge?

22:21.026 --> 22:25.031
And Peter says, you have to make up your mind in that moment that it's gonna be Jesus.

22:26.954 --> 22:27.514
It's gonna be.

22:27.534 --> 22:48.722
And then he says this, always be prepared to give an answer to everyone who asks you to give the reason for the hope that you have, but do this with gentleness and respect.

22:49.154 --> 22:50.796
Okay, so here's what Peter says.

22:51.777 --> 22:59.486
You're gonna have pushback, you gotta follow Jesus, and that's gonna, what that's going to do is it's going to lead to people asking questions about your life.

23:01.028 --> 23:01.829
It's just going to.

23:01.849 --> 23:07.917
I'll tell you a story.

23:08.077 --> 23:11.000
I didn't tell this one to the 9 a.m. crowd, because I like you all better.

23:13.864 --> 23:15.786
I love you, I do love this, I love the night.

23:18.069 --> 23:19.090
When I was a high school student,

23:19.330 --> 23:25.518
I did make a commitment to actually being, practicing abstinence until I was married.

23:25.798 --> 23:32.687
And by God's grace, shockingly, shockingly, because I ran away from him for a while, that happened.

23:34.729 --> 23:43.981
So it was interesting, in high school, as a high school student, and then as a university student, people would ask you the question, why haven't you had intercourse?

23:44.241 --> 23:45.202
They're lilliers in the room.

23:48.322 --> 23:53.989
And in that moment, I had an opportunity to say why, and sometimes I'd feel embarrassed.

23:56.432 --> 24:01.298
But what was interesting was this, in living a different life, there was questions that came.

24:03.941 --> 24:06.244
And in that, I got to answer with gentleness and respect.

24:06.584 --> 24:14.994
See, if you're here and you're, if you're a young person, I talked to some of the young people in the room, if you're here and you have had sex outside of marriage, I'm just gonna use the word to, well, to say it otherwise,

24:15.234 --> 24:20.141
God can forgive you and he loves you and you're not dirty and you can come to him for cleaning, he loves you, he cares about you.

24:21.003 --> 24:25.530
But if you do choose to wait until you're married, please do, please do.

24:26.751 --> 24:36.466
But if you do, there will come questions and there's an opportunity for you not to throw shame on other people, but to be gentle and respectful and also to go

24:36.610 --> 24:41.317
I believe God loves his people with a pure love that is for the rest of my life.

24:41.397 --> 24:43.100
He doesn't leave us or forsake us.

24:43.120 --> 24:46.905
So I want to practice that in my marriage with whomever it may be.

24:46.925 --> 24:49.689
I will become one with only one person.

24:51.392 --> 24:52.414
That's an opportunity.

24:53.295 --> 24:58.362
So on my wedding night, I had all these wild friends for my partying days and they knew, they knew.

24:58.422 --> 25:06.194
So my wife and I, when we went to leave, they did this very uncomfortable, but then amazing moment.

25:06.754 --> 25:08.396
I went to my friends and said, hey, we're leaving.

25:09.557 --> 25:10.398
And here's what they did.

25:10.418 --> 25:12.881
They went, ka-yo, ka-yo.

25:13.482 --> 25:14.743
And there was like 40 of them.

25:16.445 --> 25:18.207
40 young men shouting your name.

25:19.048 --> 25:26.077
And then my wife in her white dress comes around the corner and Lauren's a little more bashful than I am.

25:26.898 --> 25:30.262
And then my one friend, he's six, five, 300 pounds.

25:30.902 --> 25:34.066
He goes, Lauren, Lauren.

25:34.530 --> 25:39.818
And they all started doing it and they jumped around us and celebrated.

25:42.682 --> 25:45.487
Oh, what a great, I've been a bad witness in so many ways.

25:45.527 --> 25:46.308
That was a cool day.

25:48.471 --> 25:50.174
And we get to be gentle and respectful.

25:53.339 --> 25:54.841
So Peter says, you should be ready.

25:57.525 --> 26:00.469
Here's the question of somebody said, hey, I want in on Jesus.

26:00.930 --> 26:01.531
What do I do?

26:02.553 --> 26:03.474
Could you lead me to?

26:04.418 --> 26:05.079
Could you do it?

26:07.081 --> 26:09.223
Quick little reality check, most of us can't.

26:11.225 --> 26:11.886
Most of us can't.

26:13.488 --> 26:20.335
Some of you know I got the privilege of starting a church, and in order to do that, you had to go to, at the time they called it boot camp.

26:21.516 --> 26:23.218
It wasn't a very encouraging place.

26:24.540 --> 26:31.347
And at boot camp, they would test you to see if you could talk about Jesus to somebody who doesn't go to church in a way that's helpful and lead them to Jesus.

26:31.687 --> 26:34.290
And here's the reality, most of us failed, I failed.

26:35.490 --> 26:37.653
That's why we're running this everyone everywhere course.

26:38.033 --> 26:40.216
That's why Brent is running and everyone everywhere course.

26:41.037 --> 26:42.779
I'll be in attendance as well, Jason.

26:44.542 --> 26:50.609
Because we actually, part of our vision here at Foothills is that every one of us who knows Jesus gets to help somebody else know Jesus.

26:52.291 --> 26:53.613
I can actually hope that for all of you.

26:54.855 --> 26:59.561
It's part of the reason the people who started Foothills Alliance, this church is 60 years old.

26:59.581 --> 27:03.826
It got started 60 years ago because people said people need the hope of Jesus.

27:05.506 --> 27:06.147
And guess what?

27:06.167 --> 27:09.671
Our vision is not that there'd be a superstar leader or leaders.

27:10.632 --> 27:13.736
There wouldn't be an amazing spiritual celebrity.

27:14.737 --> 27:18.923
It'd be a bunch of us living everyday lives, holding out the hope of Jesus.

27:20.505 --> 27:20.925
We need it.

27:20.945 --> 27:22.087
So I'd encourage you to come.

27:23.428 --> 27:27.593
If you can't, if you can't, a quick little tool.

27:27.613 --> 27:29.796
Make a three-minute testimony.

27:29.816 --> 27:30.737
Three-minute testimony.

27:30.757 --> 27:33.000
What does that look like before you met Jesus?

27:33.721 --> 27:34.482
How you met him?

27:35.394 --> 27:36.255
and what happened after.

27:36.275 --> 27:38.518
And you take it and you write it, and then you practice it.

27:38.538 --> 27:39.359
It takes three minutes.

27:39.379 --> 27:44.405
So if somebody ever asks, and people will ask, I promise you, you can share Christ.

27:45.386 --> 27:48.950
Now some of you go, I grew up in church at a very young age.

27:49.010 --> 27:49.791
I don't even remember.

27:49.851 --> 27:51.233
I invited Jesus into my heart.

27:51.513 --> 27:52.474
What do I do then?

27:52.534 --> 27:54.236
Here's what I would say to you.

27:54.296 --> 28:00.844
There are moments and areas of your life where you go, at one point you were living as if God wasn't real, right?

28:00.864 --> 28:02.706
Some of us, we've hit a troubled time and you go,

28:02.850 --> 28:04.212
I was terrified and petrified.

28:04.272 --> 28:06.074
I didn't know what to do, so I turned to Jesus.

28:07.215 --> 28:13.363
So you talk about what happened in that section of your life, not your whole life, and then coming to Jesus and how he came through.

28:13.403 --> 28:14.765
It's good news for people.

28:18.670 --> 28:22.134
So when we suffer, we love.

28:23.856 --> 28:29.143
As some people say, trials can make you bitter or better, and we want to use them to become better.

28:29.163 --> 28:29.964
And here's the great news.

28:30.345 --> 28:31.506
God can use your suffering.

28:32.802 --> 28:33.824
God can use your suffering.

28:34.565 --> 28:37.209
It's actually the one thing God does that makes suffering makes sense.

28:38.851 --> 28:41.595
God is not the author of suffering, but he is the redeemer of it.

28:42.576 --> 28:45.921
On the cross, Jesus Christ suffered the worst fate.

28:46.242 --> 28:58.139
Not only did he die, not only was he stripped naked, not only was he ashamed and embarrassed and died of torturous death, he also endured God's anger against all evil and injustice and suffering in the world.

28:58.440 --> 28:59.922
He put all of that on Christ.

29:01.122 --> 29:03.245
And he suffered like no one will ever suffer again.

29:03.605 --> 29:03.845
Why?

29:04.226 --> 29:05.247
So that you and I don't have to.

29:05.908 --> 29:06.849
To redeem the whole world.

29:08.151 --> 29:09.232
God can redeem your pain.

29:11.015 --> 29:12.897
One other quick note on this gentleness and respect.

29:14.179 --> 29:18.404
The gentleness and respect is really about kindness.

29:19.425 --> 29:21.568
And when we do this poorly, it's outrageous.

29:21.728 --> 29:22.429
It's not helpful.

29:23.771 --> 29:26.354
There's a comedian named Pete Holmes who's

29:26.466 --> 29:27.767
His faith journey is complicated.

29:27.868 --> 29:30.010
I don't endorse everything he says nor does, okay?

29:30.030 --> 29:31.071
That's the disclaimer.

29:31.311 --> 29:34.715
But he gave this funny bit about the culture war in Christmas.

29:35.716 --> 29:36.497
Some of you have seen it.

29:37.098 --> 29:37.719
And he said, you know what?

29:37.739 --> 29:38.920
I'm not saying Merry Christmas.

29:39.020 --> 29:40.762
He's like, I didn't say Merry Christmas once this year.

29:41.863 --> 29:43.345
Didn't say it, didn't want to offend anybody.

29:44.306 --> 29:54.738
Instead, I said, may the blessing of the one true God, born of a virgin in Bethlehem,

29:55.362 --> 30:02.413
whose name is Jesus be upon you and your household forever in this winter season.

30:04.636 --> 30:05.918
He said, I think that's less offensive.

30:12.188 --> 30:13.550
Here was the point of the little skip.

30:13.570 --> 30:14.652
People laughed like that.

30:14.712 --> 30:23.666
That actually friends, if we're gonna hold up great hope, if you're here and you're not a Christian, you're not sure what you are, we just want you to meet Jesus so much.

30:24.290 --> 30:25.291
He's so good.

30:26.553 --> 30:27.274
He's so good.

30:28.636 --> 30:29.397
Foothills the rest of us.

30:29.437 --> 30:35.165
We have a job and a duty, not just to receive hope, but to the agents of hope in a dark world.

30:40.172 --> 30:48.643
See, the message of the gospel is offensive, actually, but its messengers are supposed to be winsome, an old fun word that actually we don't have to fight.

30:48.663 --> 30:49.324
We don't have to argue.

30:49.344 --> 30:50.366
We don't have to beat people up.

30:50.786 --> 30:52.008
Sometimes there's a place for debate.

30:52.068 --> 30:52.609
I like debate.

30:52.769 --> 30:53.650
I love debate.

30:55.426 --> 30:57.448
But there's a place for tenderness and gentleness.

30:57.489 --> 31:02.014
And it comes when we talk to people about the King of Kings and the Lord of Lords and the Prince of Peace.

31:05.218 --> 31:14.690
Proverbs tells us, wisdom literature says, a gentle answer turns away wrath, but a harsh word stirs up anger.

31:15.811 --> 31:22.099
See, when we feel pushback, when we feel mocked, we just need to remember that beautiful suffering points to a beautiful savior.

31:23.180 --> 31:24.882
Final thought, beautiful hope.

31:26.114 --> 31:32.803
Verse 17, it is better if it is God's will to suffer for doing good than for doing evil.

31:34.085 --> 31:40.493
For Christ also suffered once for sins, the righteous for the unrighteous, to bring you to God.

31:41.354 --> 31:43.617
He was put to death in the body but made alive in the spirit.

31:47.603 --> 31:48.224
A couple of things.

31:49.345 --> 31:52.069
Sometimes we suffer because we, we've actually, it's self-inflicted.

31:52.369 --> 31:53.331
We brought it on ourselves.

31:53.911 --> 31:55.954
Sometimes we suffer because others hurt us.

31:56.866 --> 32:00.972
Sometimes we suffer because life is just chaotic and sad and hard.

32:02.574 --> 32:05.919
And some of us, we go, God, why don't you fix my suffering?

32:06.720 --> 32:07.281
Why don't you?

32:10.025 --> 32:10.445
Two thoughts.

32:10.485 --> 32:12.749
One, that's a great prayer.

32:13.530 --> 32:17.655
If life is really hard, I would implore you to go, God, would you heal me?

32:17.696 --> 32:19.959
Would you give me wisdom to fix this relational strain?

32:20.279 --> 32:23.984
Would you give me wisdom to know how to walk through my financial difficulties?

32:24.505 --> 32:25.106
Pray.

32:26.754 --> 32:27.835
Ask him to intervene.

32:28.656 --> 32:29.678
And sometimes he does.

32:32.441 --> 32:38.108
But also, number two, sometimes he says, it's my will for you.

32:39.350 --> 32:39.990
What does that mean?

32:40.411 --> 32:41.973
God is not the author of suffering.

32:43.935 --> 32:45.337
God is not the author of suffering.

32:46.579 --> 32:48.661
God didn't make your life terrible.

32:49.102 --> 32:52.626
What he says is this, I can take what's terrible in your life and make it beautiful.

32:54.594 --> 32:56.316
What sets Christianity apart is this.

32:56.816 --> 32:59.178
This is what offends Muslims so much.

32:59.719 --> 33:01.000
As we say this, God suffers.

33:02.942 --> 33:08.547
God is a God who suffers, and he suffers to redeem, and that means he can take the suffering in your life and redeem it too.

33:12.070 --> 33:19.357
It is better to do good, better if it is God's will, to suffer for doing good than for doing evil.

33:21.099 --> 33:24.562
Foothills, we have this deep desire to train up the whole church,

33:24.706 --> 33:28.430
Everybody who knows Jesus to talk about Jesus, he's the hope of the world.

33:29.391 --> 33:30.072
He's so great.

33:31.874 --> 33:33.716
And so we're gonna head to prayer now.

33:35.458 --> 33:35.978
We're gonna pray.

33:36.999 --> 33:38.461
We're gonna talk to Jesus.

33:39.942 --> 33:40.603
See, it's interesting.

33:40.623 --> 33:43.666
We talk about how beautiful Jesus is, how much hope he is.

33:44.387 --> 33:54.578
But in the book of Isaiah, it talks about that actually when he lived among us, God's one and only son, on the day of his execution,

33:55.138 --> 33:57.201
He was beaten beyond human likeness.

33:59.605 --> 34:05.154
It says that he was marred and disfigured beyond the form of any human being.

34:09.821 --> 34:18.975
And on the cross, Jesus, the beautiful one, was made broken and marred and ugly to restore our beauty.

34:20.317 --> 34:23.282
The beauty of humanity, the beauty of being made in God's image.

34:24.482 --> 34:26.705
Have you received his hope?

34:28.228 --> 34:30.391
If you haven't, we're gonna pray and you can receive it today.

34:31.152 --> 34:39.104
If you have, you get to share it and there'll be a prayer for you on who you could share it with and how God would have you do it.

34:40.626 --> 34:41.167
So let's pray.

34:45.493 --> 34:51.021
If you're here and you've not experienced the hope and beauty of Jesus Christ, today is a great day to do that.

34:51.041 --> 34:54.226
You can pray this prayer alongside of me and your head and your heart

34:57.634 --> 34:59.076
Jesus, I receive your hope.

35:01.040 --> 35:16.105
Take my fear and my failure, reunite me with God, and redeem the broken areas of my life, including my suffering.

35:16.125 --> 35:18.188
Thank you that you suffered to save me.

35:19.991 --> 35:21.554
Please put your spirit within me.

35:26.434 --> 35:28.758
The second prayer is for those of us who have received Jesus.

35:29.799 --> 35:31.161
We're just gonna pause, we're gonna listen.

35:31.482 --> 35:39.274
Sometimes the Spirit of God speaks to us in our thoughts, sometimes he whispers stuff to us, sometimes he reminds us of scripture, because he wants to lead and guide us.

35:40.736 --> 35:49.930
So we're gonna invite the Lord Jesus to show us who we might nudge towards this kingdom and how we should do that.

35:51.593 --> 35:55.058
So here's the simple prayer, come Spirit of God, we know you're here.

35:56.130 --> 36:09.948
Would you show us who you would have us nudge towards your kingdom?

36:09.968 --> 36:11.510
And then Lord, how would you have us do it?

36:20.100 --> 36:21.963
And so Jesus, we turn our eyes to you.

36:22.944 --> 36:24.466
You are the author.

36:25.890 --> 36:27.592
and the perfecter of our faith.

36:28.733 --> 36:33.758
We pray today that you would give the gift of faith to many in this room and online.

36:35.039 --> 36:39.564
And then, Lord, we pray that you would strengthen those of us who feel weak.

36:39.584 --> 36:46.311
You would give us great strength by your Holy Spirit to hold out the reason for the hope we have.

36:47.252 --> 36:53.138
And Jesus, we ask in your name that you would continue to make Foothills Alliance Church

36:53.570 --> 37:05.251
a church where the hope of Jesus is found and where his people go out to spread the good news of your kingdom, your love, your forgiveness, and your return.

37:05.953 --> 37:07.756
And we pray all this in Jesus' beautiful name.

37:08.538 --> 37:08.818
Amen.

